---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Header from "../../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Slanj Website Extras Case Study | Ross Lyall Portfolio"
  description="Case study for embedded website tools built for the Slanj website."
>
  <div class="page-shell">
    <Header />

    <main>
      <section class="case-hero case-hero--slanj">
        <a class="back-link" href="/">← Back to portfolio</a>

        <p class="eyebrow">Case Study / Embedded Website Tools</p>
        <h1>Slanj Website Extras</h1>
        <p class="case-hero__lead">
          Practical tools added to an existing Squarespace retail website to
          improve customer journeys, reduce confusion and make useful
          information easier to access.
        </p>

        <div class="case-meta">
          <span>Squarespace</span>
          <span>JavaScript</span>
          <span>Retail UX</span>
          <span>Customer Journey Tools</span>
          <span>Embedded Features</span>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
          <h2>Some customer journeys needed more guidance than normal website pages could give.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The Slanj website already had standard product and information
            pages, but some tasks needed a more guided experience. Customers
            often need help choosing the right appointment type or browsing
            tartans in a clearer way.
          </p>

          <p>
            Rebuilding the whole website was not the aim. The better solution
            was to add focused embedded tools that improved specific customer
            journeys while working within the existing Squarespace site.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">The solution</p>
          <h2>Small tools that make the existing site more useful.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            The extras are designed as practical add-ons: they sit alongside the
            existing website and help customers complete specific tasks more
            confidently.
          </p>

          <p>
            This approach is useful because it gives the business more flexible
            functionality without forcing a full platform rebuild or a major
            redesign.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Tools included</p>
          <h2>What the extras do</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="feature-grid">
          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Tartan directory</h3>
            <p>
              A more useful way for customers to browse tartans, helping turn a
              large amount of information into something easier to explore.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Appointment wizard</h3>
            <p>
              A guided flow that helps customers choose the correct appointment
              type before contacting or booking with the shop.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Customer guidance</h3>
            <p>
              The tools are designed to reduce uncertainty by asking better
              questions and presenting clearer next steps.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Existing platform fit</h3>
            <p>
              Built to work with an existing Squarespace site rather than
              replacing the whole website.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>05</span>
            <h3>Retail workflow support</h3>
            <p>
              Helps bridge the gap between what customers think they need and
              what staff actually need to know.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="feature-card">
            <span>06</span>
            <h3>Future expansion</h3>
            <p>
              The same approach could support more guided tools, product
              selectors and customer self-service features.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-overview">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Design thinking</p>
          <h2>The aim was to improve the journey without making the website feel complicated.</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="case-copy">
          <p>
            A good embedded tool should feel like part of the customer journey,
            not like a separate system dropped onto the page. The design needs
            to be clear, lightweight and focused on the next useful action.
          </p>

          <p>
            For the appointment wizard, the important part is not just the final
            answer. The value is in guiding customers through the decision so
            they are less likely to choose the wrong option.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">Build approach</p>
          <h2>Why this works well for Squarespace</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="flow-grid flow-grid--four">
          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Keep the main site</h3>
            <p>
              The existing Squarespace site remains in place, avoiding the cost
              and disruption of a rebuild.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Add targeted tools</h3>
            <p>
              Specific customer problems are solved with focused embedded
              features rather than broad redesigns.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Guide decisions</h3>
            <p>
              The tools help customers understand what they need before staff
              have to step in.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="flow-card">
            <span>04</span>
            <h3>Improve over time</h3>
            <p>
              New tools can be added as more awkward customer journeys are
              identified.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section">
        <div class="section-heading">
          <p class="eyebrow">What I learned</p>
          <h2>Useful lessons from building it</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="lesson-list">
          <article>
            <h3>Not every improvement needs a full rebuild</h3>
            <p>
              Sometimes the most useful improvement is a focused tool that fixes
              one awkward part of the journey.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Retail websites need to reduce uncertainty</h3>
            <p>
              Customers often do not know the internal categories or appointment
              types. A guided flow can translate customer needs into staff-ready
              information.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article>
            <h3>Embedded tools are a useful middle ground</h3>
            <p>
              They allow an existing platform to become more powerful without
              losing the simplicity of the main website.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="case-section case-next">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Future improvements</p>
          <h2>Where the embedded tools could go next</h2>
        </div>

        <ul>
          <li>Add more guided product or outfit selection tools.</li>
          <li>Improve staff handover information from customer flows.</li>
          <li>Connect enquiries more directly to internal systems.</li>
          <li>Add analytics to see where customers get stuck.</li>
          <li>Turn more repeated staff questions into self-service journeys.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>